SIMPLE: logic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Logic
<hw>Log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>logike</ets>,
F. <ets>logique</ets>, L. <ets>logica</ets>, <ets>logice</ets>, Gr.
<grk>logikh`</grk> (sc. <grk>te`chnh</grk>), fr. <grk>logiko`s</grk>
belonging to speaking or reason, fr. <grk>lo`gos</grk> speech, reason,
<grk>le`gein</grk> to say, speak. See <er>Legend</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The science or art of exact reasoning, or of pure and
formal thought, or of the laws according to which the processes of pure
thinking should be conducted; the science of the formation and
application of general notions; the science of generalization, judgment,
classification, reasoning, and systematic arrangement; the science of
correct reasoning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 866 --></p>

<p><q><qex>Logic</qex> is the science of the laws of thought, as
thought; that is, of the necessary conditions to which thought,
considered in itself, is subject.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Logic</xex> is distinguished as <xex>pure</xex> and
<xex>applied</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Pure logic</xex> is a science of the
form, or of the formal laws, of thinking, and not of the matter.
<xex>Applied logic</xex> teaches the application of the forms of
thinking to those objects about which men do think.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Abp.
Thomson.</au></rj></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A treatise on logic; <as>as, Mill's
<ex>Logic</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>correct reasoning; <as>as, I can't see any
<ex>logic</ex> in his argument</as>; also, sound judgment; <as>as, the
<ex>logic</ex> of surrender was uncontestable</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The path of reasoning used in any specific argument;
<as>as, his <ex>logic</ex> was irrefutable</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Electronics, Computers)</fld> <def>A function of an
electrical circuit (called a gate) that mimics certain elementary binary
logical operations on electrical signals, such as AND, OR, or NOT;
<as>as, a <ex>logic</ex> circuit; the arithmetic and <ex>logic</ex>
unit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Logical</ent>⟦br⟧
